Students on tour
in a strange land.

220
00:18:58,155 --> 00:19:00,042
Their tiny bus
disabled.

221
00:19:00,107 --> 00:19:02,660
They'll be gone
in the morning.

222
00:19:02,731 --> 00:19:04,586
They're staying here
tonight?

223
00:19:04,651 --> 00:19:08,928
I probably should have turned
them away, but the quality
of mercy is not strained.

224
00:19:09,003 --> 00:19:12,265
It's being strained right now.
Why didn't you send them
to a hotel?

225
00:19:12,331 --> 00:19:14,306
There isn't a vacancy
in town.

226
00:19:14,379 --> 00:19:17,892
But if you insist,
I'll just tell them...
they have to leave.

227
00:19:17,963 --> 00:19:20,516
Well, they have
to go somewhere.

228
00:19:20,587 --> 00:19:23,936
What about this new place?
This La Dolce Vista?

229
00:19:24,011 --> 00:19:25,899
Full up, sir.

230
00:19:25,963 --> 00:19:28,003
Well,
they can't stay here.

231
00:19:28,075 --> 00:19:31,620
Check around
and find something.
Yes, sir.

232
00:19:31,691 --> 00:19:33,764
Maurice!

233
00:19:33,835 --> 00:19:37,512
Oh, we had a splendid hike.
Quite exhilarating.

234
00:19:37,579 --> 00:19:40,579
This is Miss Allison,
Miss Stevens. Mr. Talbot.
How do you do?

235
00:19:40,651 --> 00:19:43,106
How do you do?

236
00:19:43,179 --> 00:19:46,856
Hi.
Miss Allison is
the girls' chaperone.

237
00:19:46,923 --> 00:19:50,087
Oh! Where's Cedric?
I had him carried up
to your bedroom.

238
00:19:50,155 --> 00:19:52,129
<i>Oh, splendid.!</i>

239
00:19:52,203 --> 00:19:56,065
- Uh... who's Cedric?
<i>- M</i>iss Allison's parakeet.

240
00:19:56,139 --> 00:19:59,652
This is such a lovely place.
And the view from the terrace!

241
00:19:59,723 --> 00:20:01,665
Quite breathtaking.

242
00:20:01,739 --> 00:20:04,357
Thank you.
Now, if you'll excuse me.

243
00:20:04,427 --> 00:20:07,111
Maurice,
make the ladies comfortable.

244
00:20:10,219 --> 00:20:14,310
Well, really!
He acts as though
he owns the place.

245
00:20:14,379 --> 00:20:18,176
I was hoping
he'd be better this year.
What's wrong with him?

246
00:20:18,251 --> 00:20:21,317
This is a story
I wish I didn't have to tell.

247
00:20:21,387 --> 00:20:23,875
Years ago
his family owned this place.

248
00:20:23,946 --> 00:20:26,663
There were
financial reverses.
They lost it.

249
00:20:26,731 --> 00:20:30,789
That's when
you bought it.
Yes.

250
00:20:30,859 --> 00:20:33,958
Then the war came along.

251
00:20:34,027 --> 00:20:36,962
He was standing sentry duty
at an ammunition dump.

252
00:20:37,035 --> 00:20:38,758
Blew up.
Really?

253
00:20:38,827 --> 00:20:40,714
Left him slightly
shell-shocked.

254
00:20:40,779 --> 00:20:43,015
You wouldn't know it
to look at him.
No.

255
00:20:43,083 --> 00:20:46,345
It's like looking at
a magnificent castle
with a weak tower.

256
00:20:47,787 --> 00:20:50,308
Isn't it dangerous
having him roaming around?

257
00:20:50,379 --> 00:20:52,713
No, no, no.
He's absolutely harmless...

258
00:20:52,779 --> 00:20:54,819
except for one small
mental quirk.
Yes?

259
00:20:54,891 --> 00:20:57,312
He thinks
he still owns the place.

260
00:20:57,387 --> 00:21:01,282
I let him come every year
to stay a while. It seems
to calm his nerves.

261
00:21:01,355 --> 00:21:04,388
In case he should say something
unusual, play along with him.
Oh, yes.

262
00:21:04,459 --> 00:21:06,369
What an interesting
case history!

263
00:21:06,443 --> 00:21:09,988
Has he any money?
Only his
government pension.

264
00:21:10,059 --> 00:21:12,645
Naturally,
I do what I can.
Oh, Maurice!

265
00:21:12,715 --> 00:21:15,846
I think that's why
I'm so fond of you.

266
00:21:15,915 --> 00:21:18,184
You're always
thinking of others.

267
00:21:18,251 --> 00:21:21,928
I really think
a psychiatrist
would help him.

268
00:21:21,995 --> 00:21:24,613
Undoubtedly.
But it's none
of your affair.

269
00:21:24,682 --> 00:21:26,952
Sandy's a major
in psychology.

270
00:21:27,019 --> 00:21:29,604
She's quite a fanatic
on the subject.
The dear child.

271
00:21:29,675 --> 00:21:31,268
<i>Maurice?</i>
Yes, sir?

272
00:21:31,339 --> 00:21:34,688
Have these shined,
will you?
<i>Yes, sir.</i>

273
00:21:34,763 --> 00:21:38,145
- Draw my bath.
Lay out my clothes.
- Yes, sir. Yes, sir.

274
00:21:42,571 --> 00:21:44,774
Analysis
would help him!

275
00:21:44,842 --> 00:21:46,817
Or a good talking-to!

276
00:21:46,891 --> 00:21:49,444
He may be shell-shocked,
but he's not helpless.

277
00:21:49,515 --> 00:21:53,312
The idea!
Treating you as if
you were his servant.

278
00:22:15,595 --> 00:22:17,832
Uh, hello.

279
00:22:19,819 --> 00:22:21,706
Hello.

280
00:22:23,211 --> 00:22:26,855
Uh, Mr. Talbot?
Mmm?

281
00:22:26,923 --> 00:22:30,535
Uh... have you owned
this place very long?

282
00:22:30,603 --> 00:22:32,872
Quite some time.

283
00:22:32,939 --> 00:22:36,322
You must be
very proud of it.

284
00:22:36,395 --> 00:22:40,257
Yes, I am.
Unfortunately...

285
00:22:40,331 --> 00:22:44,127
<i>since the war,</i>
<i>I've only been able</i>
<i>to come here once a year.</i>

286
00:22:44,203 --> 00:22:48,327
Oh. It must've been
a terrible war.

287
00:22:48,395 --> 00:22:50,883
They usually are.

288
00:22:50,955 --> 00:22:55,046
Yes, well--
I'd like to talk to you
about it sometime.

289
00:22:56,651 --> 00:22:59,138
About what?
The war.

290
00:22:59,211 --> 00:23:01,066
The war?

291
00:23:01,131 --> 00:23:04,230
Yes. I have a feeling
I can help.

292
00:23:05,611 --> 00:23:08,458
[ Chuckles ]
I doubt it.

293
00:23:08,523 --> 00:23:10,978
It's over.

294
00:23:11,051 --> 00:23:15,426
<i>♪♪ [ Romantic Music</i>
<i>On Record Player ]</i>

295
00:23:15,499 --> 00:23:18,662
What are you doing here?
You told me
to lay out your clothes.

296
00:23:18,731 --> 00:23:21,513
I'll do it.
Find a place
for those women.

297
00:23:21,579 --> 00:23:25,191
Yes, sir.

298
00:23:25,259 --> 00:23:28,390
<i>[ Door Opens,</i>
<i>Closes ]</i>

299
00:23:28,459 --> 00:23:31,274
<i>[ Knock At Door ]</i>
Come in.

300
00:23:35,211 --> 00:23:37,993
Mr. Talbot?
Yes?

301
00:23:39,883 --> 00:23:42,883
I was wondering if we
could have our little talk now.
I'm very sorry--

302
00:23:42,955 --> 00:23:46,271
Please, it's terribly important.
Why don't you sit down?
Look--

303
00:23:46,347 --> 00:23:49,609
No, no. Not there.
On the couch.

304
00:23:49,675 --> 00:23:51,530
What do you mean,
on the--

305
00:23:51,595 --> 00:23:53,984
Now try and relax.
Lie down.

306
00:23:54,059 --> 00:23:57,572
Lie down?
It's for
your own good.

307
00:23:57,643 --> 00:23:59,497
There.

308
00:24:00,779 --> 00:24:03,746
<i>[ Turns Record Player Off]</i>

309
00:24:03,819 --> 00:24:07,168
Really, Mr. Talbot,
you must try and relax.

310
00:24:12,842 --> 00:24:16,138
Now, where would you
like to begin?

311
00:24:18,539 --> 00:24:21,060
I... really don't know.

312
00:24:21,131 --> 00:24:23,105
Where would you suggest?

313
00:24:23,179 --> 00:24:27,783
Well, let's start
with... the war.

314
00:24:29,258 --> 00:24:33,055
That war really...
bothers you, doesn't it?

315
00:24:34,635 --> 00:24:37,504
You were in the army.

316
00:24:37,579 --> 00:24:40,361
I thought
I was in the navy.

317
00:24:40,426 --> 00:24:43,688
No. You were
in the army,

318
00:24:43,754 --> 00:24:46,820
standing sentry duty...

319
00:24:46,890 --> 00:24:49,094
at an ammunition dump...

320
00:24:49,162 --> 00:24:51,715
that... blew up.

321
00:24:54,027 --> 00:24:56,230
Do you remember that?

322
00:24:58,410 --> 00:25:02,720
All I remember is
being officer in a P.T. boat.

323
00:25:02,795 --> 00:25:05,478
Don't you see?
That's your subconscious...

324
00:25:05,547 --> 00:25:08,067
substituting fantasy
for fact.
Look, young lady--

325
00:25:08,139 --> 00:25:12,514
That's why you still think
you own this place.

326
00:25:14,411 --> 00:25:16,298
Don't I?

327
00:25:18,411 --> 00:25:22,819
No. Really, Mr. Talbot,
you must face reality.

328
00:25:22,891 --> 00:25:25,160
Your family
lost this house.

329
00:25:25,227 --> 00:25:29,450
Mr. Clavell bought it,
turned it into a hotel.

330
00:25:31,371 --> 00:25:33,225
A hotel?

331
00:25:33,291 --> 00:25:35,941
Mm-hmm.

332
00:25:43,563 --> 00:25:45,450
La Dolce Vista?

333
00:25:45,515 --> 00:25:47,970
That's right.

334
00:25:50,475 --> 00:25:52,864
People pay him
to stay here?

335
00:25:52,938 --> 00:25:55,011
Yes.

336
00:25:55,083 --> 00:25:57,287
It's a hotel!

337
00:25:57,355 --> 00:26:00,137
Right! Mr. Talbot,
you don't know how happy
you've made me.

338
00:26:00,202 --> 00:26:04,480
I knew if I could just talk
to you, I could help you.
Oh, you have.

339
00:26:04,554 --> 00:26:06,976
Suddenly all the pieces
have fallen into place.

340
00:26:07,051 --> 00:26:10,247
Mr. Clavell will be
so thrilled to hear
you've recovered.
Mmm.

341
00:26:10,314 --> 00:26:13,282
I'll go tell him.
No, no, no, no.

342
00:26:13,354 --> 00:26:15,907
Let me tell him.

343
00:26:20,043 --> 00:26:22,661
Hmm.
[ Door Slams ]

344
00:26:22,731 --> 00:26:27,750
♪♪ [ Singing Along
With The Radio ]

345
00:26:33,995 --> 00:26:36,646
♪♪ [ Singing Continues ]
[ Radio Off]

346
00:26:36,715 --> 00:26:39,366
You can tell Maria
to stop praying.

347
00:26:39,435 --> 00:26:43,395
Her friend didn't survive
the crisis.

348
00:26:43,466 --> 00:26:45,888
Excuse me.
I have some duties.

349
00:26:45,963 --> 00:26:49,411
A majordomo's day
is never done.
Yours is.

350
00:26:49,482 --> 00:26:52,898
Don't think of yourself
as a majordomo.

351
00:26:52,971 --> 00:26:55,970
More like a sentry
at an ammunition dump...

352
00:26:56,042 --> 00:26:58,431
that's about
to blow up.

353
00:27:00,267 --> 00:27:02,852
Your room
or mine?
Yours.

354
00:27:02,922 --> 00:27:05,825
This way.
Oh.

355
00:27:16,491 --> 00:27:18,466
You're a thief.
Yes, sir.

356
00:27:18,539 --> 00:27:21,288
And a liar.
Completely untrustworthy.
Yes, sir.

357
00:27:21,354 --> 00:27:24,486
A thief and a liar, yes.
But not untrustworthy.

358
00:27:24,555 --> 00:27:27,653
I really don't think
this is the proper time
to talk the matter out.

359
00:27:27,722 --> 00:27:30,756
Not while your mind
is bristling with
negative thoughts towards me.

360
00:27:30,827 --> 00:27:33,729
I haven't even begun
to bristle!

361
00:27:33,803 --> 00:27:38,472
Turning my house into
a hotel!
How easy for you
to say " my house,"

362
00:27:38,538 --> 00:27:41,157
yet you're never here.
What has that got
to do with it?

363
00:27:41,227 --> 00:27:43,299
When her windows are stuck,
do you care?

364
00:27:43,371 --> 00:27:47,048
No. You're in New York.
I, Maurice,
have to unstick them.

365
00:27:47,114 --> 00:27:50,278
On a cold night
when her radiators knock,
are you here?

366
00:27:50,346 --> 00:27:52,201
No.
I have to warm them up.

367
00:27:52,266 --> 00:27:56,161
And when her plumbing goes out,
who's there to unclog her?
Maurice.

368
00:27:56,235 --> 00:28:00,163
You're like a husband
who's only with his wife
one month a year.

369
00:28:00,235 --> 00:28:03,366
It's the man who lives
with her the rest of the year
who deserves the credit.

370
00:28:03,434 --> 00:28:06,980
Let's just say
I don't care for what
you've turned my wife into!

371
00:28:07,051 --> 00:28:09,734
And what have I done
with the profits?
That's a good question.

372
00:28:09,802 --> 00:28:13,380
Painted her.
Put in a new garden wall,
a fountain, a patio.

373
00:28:13,450 --> 00:28:16,549
I've even replenished
the wine cellar.
Not to mention your wallet!

374
00:28:16,619 --> 00:28:19,466
Oh!

375
00:28:19,531 --> 00:28:22,662
Any personal gain
was of secondary importance.

376
00:28:22,731 --> 00:28:26,179
Your smile of appreciation
when you came here every year,

377
00:28:26,251 --> 00:28:29,284
that was my real...
my real reward.

378
00:28:35,403 --> 00:28:38,698
You will tell your guests
to find themselves
another hotel.

379
00:28:38,762 --> 00:28:42,177
As for you and your accomplices,
pack your bags and be out
of here in the morning.

380
00:28:42,250 --> 00:28:45,698
Sir?
I wish you'd sleep
on that decision.

381
00:28:45,771 --> 00:28:49,087
Tomorrow we'll probably
both be laughing
about this entire matter.

382
00:28:49,162 --> 00:28:52,478
We might both be laughing,
but not in the same house.

383
00:28:52,554 --> 00:28:56,067
Sir, may I please ask
one last favor?

384
00:28:56,138 --> 00:29:00,164
Margaret, the girls' chaperone,
she's been coming through
with tours for some time.

385
00:29:00,234 --> 00:29:03,879
We've become rather close.
We've even made plans
for the future.

386
00:29:03,947 --> 00:29:06,281
She thinks I'm the owner.

387
00:29:06,346 --> 00:29:09,859
Will you please
let me explain it to her
in my own way?

388
00:29:09,930 --> 00:29:14,087
All right, but I have
the feeling I'm not doing
Margaret any favor.

389
00:29:14,155 --> 00:29:16,456
Thank you, sir.
I'll talk to her right away.

390
00:29:16,522 --> 00:29:19,272
We should be leaving
in half an hour to meet
Miss Fellini at the station.

391
00:29:19,338 --> 00:29:21,226
I'll pick her up myself.
Please, sir.

392
00:29:21,291 --> 00:29:25,000
As long as I'm here,
I would like to attend
to my duties.

393
00:29:27,018 --> 00:29:29,800
Just for
my own information,

394
00:29:29,867 --> 00:29:33,925
how long has this
been a hotel?

395
00:29:33,994 --> 00:29:36,744
Six years.

396
00:29:37,930 --> 00:29:41,247
It was a fine hotel
with a triple " A" rating.

397
00:29:41,322 --> 00:29:43,689
Conrad Hilton would have
been proud to own it.

398
00:29:43,754 --> 00:29:47,399
I'm surprised
you didn't sell it to him.

399
00:29:47,466 --> 00:29:49,408
The deed
is in your name.

400
00:29:53,898 --> 00:29:58,568
<i>E piacere rivederla,</i>
<i>signorina.</i>
<i>Grazie, Maurice.</i>

401
00:29:58,634 --> 00:30:01,481
What did he say?
That it was nice
to see me.

402
00:30:01,547 --> 00:30:03,008
Oh.

403
00:30:03,082 --> 00:30:05,951
<i>Le trovo bene,</i>
<i>Maurice.</i>
Lisa, please.

404
00:30:06,026 --> 00:30:09,572
Don't pat the servants.
Maurice? He's more
than a servant.

405
00:30:09,643 --> 00:30:13,669
Yes. I found that out today!
Keep your eyes on the road.

406
00:30:13,739 --> 00:30:16,357
Robert, you're terribly
sharp with Maurice.

407
00:30:16,426 --> 00:30:18,881
What's wrong?

408
00:30:18,954 --> 00:30:21,288
How would you feel
if you found out Brutus...

409
00:30:21,355 --> 00:30:24,802
<i>was your majordomo,</i>
<i>Lucrezia Borgia your cook...</i>

410
00:30:24,874 --> 00:30:29,217
and Benedict Arnold
your upstairs maid?
<i>Cosi ai combinato?</i>

411
00:30:29,291 --> 00:30:32,706
<i>Questa villa resta vuota</i>
<i>undici mese al'anno.</i>

412
00:30:32,779 --> 00:30:34,339
<i>Alora mi son detto,</i>
<i>"Che peccato.</i>

413
00:30:34,410 --> 00:30:37,890
Perche non hai pensato
convertirlo in un albergo."

414
00:30:37,962 --> 00:30:41,159
A hotel!
Mmm.
Filled with tourists.

415
00:30:41,226 --> 00:30:44,641
Look.
He even advertises.
[ Laughing ]

416
00:30:44,714 --> 00:30:46,569
Don't laugh.
You're only encouraging him.

417
00:30:46,634 --> 00:30:50,529
<i>Ci sono una povera vecchia</i>
<i>con sei Bambini indifesi...</i>

418
00:30:50,602 --> 00:30:52,937
<i>e lui le butta fuori</i>
<i>nella strada.!</i>

419
00:30:53,002 --> 00:30:54,889
<i>E vero?</i>
<i>E vero.</i>

420
00:30:54,955 --> 00:30:56,481
I can't believe it.
Believe what?

421
00:30:56,554 --> 00:30:59,588
That you could be so cruel
to throw out
into the street...

422
00:30:59,659 --> 00:31:03,433
an old woman
and six helpless children.

423
00:31:03,499 --> 00:31:05,866
They're not children.
They're--

424
00:31:05,931 --> 00:31:08,418
What?
Not children!

425
00:31:08,490 --> 00:31:11,839
<i>Si deve solo gli lasciare</i>
<i>qui ancora una notte.</i>
<i>Se ne vanno nella mattina.</i>

426
00:31:11,914 --> 00:31:15,689
Why can't they stay
one night?

427
00:31:15,754 --> 00:31:17,609
They are leaving
in the morning.

428
00:31:17,674 --> 00:31:22,213
I don't want
anybody there tonight.
Do you?

429
00:31:22,282 --> 00:31:26,025
Roberto, what can
one night hurt?

430
00:31:26,091 --> 00:31:29,091
<i>A raggione.</i>
<i>Che importa--</i>
You keep out of this!

431
00:31:29,163 --> 00:31:32,807
And don't you listen to him.
I've never seen you
like this before.

432
00:31:32,874 --> 00:31:37,064
You're upset.
Of course I'm upset.

433
00:31:37,130 --> 00:31:40,872
It's been ten months
since we've seen each other.
Whose fault is that?

434
00:31:40,939 --> 00:31:43,273
<i>Mi fa male quindi</i>
<i>di discordare.</i>
[ Laughing ]

435
00:31:43,338 --> 00:31:47,877
Isn't he sweet?
He said it upsets him
to hear us argue.

436
00:31:47,946 --> 00:31:52,321
There's nothing to argue about.
He's already told'em to leave.

437
00:31:56,042 --> 00:32:00,745
You did tell your friend,
uh, Margaret, didn't you?

438
00:32:00,810 --> 00:32:04,639
<i>Come pottevo.</i>
<i>Stava faciento il bagno.</i>
<i>Non siamo poi cosi tanto amici.</i>

439
00:32:04,714 --> 00:32:08,097
[ Laughing ]
Don't talk to her.
Talk to me!

440
00:32:08,171 --> 00:32:12,294
What's the big joke?
He said,
how could he tell her?

441
00:32:12,362 --> 00:32:16,934
She was taking a bath,
and they're not
that friendly.

442
00:32:17,002 --> 00:32:18,857
I don't think that's funny.

443
00:32:18,922 --> 00:32:22,021
<i>Mi preoccupa.</i>
<i>Aperso tutto e suo spirito.</i>
[ Laughing ]

444
00:32:22,090 --> 00:32:26,912
He said he's worried
about you. You've lost
your sense of humor.

445
00:32:26,986 --> 00:32:29,735
Mm-hmm.
I'll get it back
when he leaves.

446
00:32:41,866 --> 00:32:45,063
I don't think
you should go in with me.

447
00:32:45,130 --> 00:32:47,039
Why not?

448
00:32:47,114 --> 00:32:49,503
The hotel guests.

449
00:32:49,578 --> 00:32:52,644
How will it look
if we come in together?

450
00:32:52,714 --> 00:32:54,569
All right.

451
00:32:54,634 --> 00:32:58,017
I'll park the car
and come in through
the servants' entrance.

452
00:33:00,523 --> 00:33:03,938
I wouldn't want you to lose
your triple " A" rating.

453
00:33:08,234 --> 00:33:11,016
[ Engine Revs ]

454
00:33:26,314 --> 00:33:29,129
Miss Allison,
Signorina Fellini.

455
00:33:29,194 --> 00:33:31,780
<i>Buon giorno.</i>
Good afternoon.

456
00:33:34,282 --> 00:33:38,057
[ Whispering ]
Who's she?
A schoolteacher.

457
00:33:39,883 --> 00:33:42,468
She doesn't look
like a schoolteacher.

458
00:33:42,538 --> 00:33:45,604
Margaret, if beauty
symbolized occupation,

459
00:33:45,674 --> 00:33:49,471
one might mistake you for
a former star of the cinema.
Oh, Maurice!

460
00:33:56,842 --> 00:33:58,882
[ Knocking ]

461
00:33:58,954 --> 00:34:01,889
<i>[ Shower Water Running ]</i>

462
00:34:07,242 --> 00:34:11,039
<i>[ Lisa ]</i>
<i>Robert.</i>
[ Chuckling ]

463
00:34:15,754 --> 00:34:18,754
Oh... not now.
Why not?

464
00:34:18,826 --> 00:34:21,215
She's taking a shower.
Who is?

465
00:34:21,290 --> 00:34:23,559
Sandy.
Who's Sandy?

466
00:34:23,626 --> 00:34:26,441
The girl
I'm rooming with.

467
00:34:30,634 --> 00:34:33,023
You're rooming
with someone?
Mm-hmm.

468
00:34:33,098 --> 00:34:36,131
I'll kill that Maurice!
Wait!
It's not his fault.

469
00:34:36,202 --> 00:34:38,406
It's not?
If he moved everyone around...

470
00:34:38,474 --> 00:34:42,817
so I could be alone
in the room next to yours,
how would it look?

471
00:34:42,891 --> 00:34:45,029
You better leave.

472
00:34:46,058 --> 00:34:48,393
We'll have dinner
on my terrace.

473
00:34:48,458 --> 00:34:52,167
There isn't enough room
for nine people.
What nine people?

474
00:34:52,234 --> 00:34:54,885
They'll suspect something
if we don't eat with them.

475
00:34:54,954 --> 00:34:57,638
Hurry.
She might see you.
Oh.

476
00:34:57,706 --> 00:35:00,640
Be careful!

477
00:35:00,714 --> 00:35:03,748
What am I sneaking
around for? It's my...
Shh!

478
00:35:03,818 --> 00:35:05,673
house.

479
00:36:20,842 --> 00:36:24,704
<i>[ Sandy ]</i>
<i>You'd better wait.</i>

480
00:36:24,778 --> 00:36:29,829
Miss Allison hasn't made
her bed check yet, and
she's already suspicious.

481
00:36:31,466 --> 00:36:33,539
Oh.
Of what?

482
00:36:33,610 --> 00:36:35,497
You and Mr. Talbot.

483
00:36:35,562 --> 00:36:38,246
What about us?

484
00:36:38,314 --> 00:36:40,485
Don't get me wrong.

485
00:36:40,554 --> 00:36:43,718
I think it's terribly exciting.
All the girls do.

486
00:36:43,786 --> 00:36:46,786
Two people in love,
being in a romantic place
like this.

487
00:36:46,858 --> 00:36:50,819
<i>It's about the dreamiest thing</i>
<i>I've ever heard of!</i>

488
00:36:50,890 --> 00:36:54,818
I'm going downstairs
to get some warm milk.

489
00:36:54,890 --> 00:36:57,737
<i>Warm milk?</i>

490
00:36:57,802 --> 00:37:01,893
He looks more like
the champagne type to me.

491
00:37:07,498 --> 00:37:09,408
[ Door Slams ]

492
00:37:16,938 --> 00:37:20,648
[ Door Opening ]
Good night, girls!
Lights out now.

493
00:37:22,378 --> 00:37:26,502
Uh, I was just going
downstairs...

494
00:37:26,570 --> 00:37:28,457
to get some warm milk.

495
00:37:39,626 --> 00:37:45,028
<i>♪♪ [ Romantic ]</i>

496
00:37:48,714 --> 00:37:52,292
<i>♪♪ [ Music Continues ]</i>

497
00:38:00,234 --> 00:38:03,529
<i>[ Door Opens ]</i>

498
00:38:06,378 --> 00:38:09,673
I got the warm milk.

499
00:38:22,698 --> 00:38:25,698
[ Door Opens ]

500
00:38:25,770 --> 00:38:27,875
Sandy?
Yes, ma'am.

501
00:38:27,946 --> 00:38:30,084
Lights out now.

502
00:38:30,154 --> 00:38:32,772
Good night, girls.

503
00:38:32,841 --> 00:38:35,875
Good night.
Good night.

504
00:38:35,946 --> 00:38:39,262
[ Sighs ]

505
00:38:39,338 --> 00:38:42,055
She'll be asleep
in ten minutes.

506
00:38:42,122 --> 00:38:44,872
So will I.

507
00:38:44,938 --> 00:38:48,353
But he's waiting for you.
I can hear the music.

508
00:38:48,426 --> 00:38:53,511
I really don't know
where a girl your age
gets ideas like that.

509
00:38:53,578 --> 00:38:57,636
I have no intention
of going to Mr. Talbot's room.

510
00:38:57,706 --> 00:39:01,829
I'm going--
Yes, I'm going to finish
my milk...

511
00:39:01,897 --> 00:39:04,069
and go to sleep.

512
00:39:20,778 --> 00:39:25,285
<i>[ Bells Ringing ]</i>

513
00:40:01,898 --> 00:40:04,386
Mm-hmm.

514
00:40:11,465 --> 00:40:13,505
Mmm.

515
00:40:28,714 --> 00:40:30,983
Good morning.

516
00:40:31,050 --> 00:40:33,603
Morning?
Mm-hmm.

517
00:40:35,402 --> 00:40:37,507
What happened
to last night?

518
00:40:37,578 --> 00:40:41,571
Everybody looked suspicious,
and Sandy knew about us.

519
00:40:41,641 --> 00:40:45,504
I couldn't leave.
It would've been too obvious.

520
00:40:45,577 --> 00:40:48,196
Sandy seems to know
about everything.

521
00:40:48,266 --> 00:40:50,153
Now I know what
she's doing in Europe.

522
00:40:50,218 --> 00:40:53,633
Her neighbors decided
to chip in and send her.

523
00:40:53,705 --> 00:40:56,291
Mmm.
<i>[ Horn Honking ]</i>

524
00:40:56,362 --> 00:40:59,329
What's that?
They are getting ready
to leave.

525
00:40:59,402 --> 00:41:01,922
Oh. Good.

526
00:41:01,993 --> 00:41:06,532
I promised to come down
and say good-bye.
Send'em a letter.

527
00:41:06,601 --> 00:41:10,530
It'll only take a minute.
No, Lisa.

528
00:41:10,602 --> 00:41:13,187
Come on.
You should come down
and say good-bye too.

529
00:41:13,258 --> 00:41:15,265
I'll wave to'em
from the terrace.

530
00:41:15,337 --> 00:41:17,574
Teenagers are like
the H-bomb.

531
00:41:17,642 --> 00:41:22,017
When they go off,
it's much better
to observe them from a distance.

532
00:41:37,354 --> 00:41:39,329
<i>[ Girl ]</i>
<i>Bye, Mr. Talbot.</i>

533
00:41:39,402 --> 00:41:41,823
Good-bye!
Good-bye, Mr. Talbot.

534
00:41:41,898 --> 00:41:44,386
<i>[ Girls Together ]</i>
<i>Good-bye, Mr. Talbot.</i>

535
00:41:45,449 --> 00:41:47,904
Good morning, sir.
Your orange juice.

536
00:41:47,977 --> 00:41:51,425
Not orange juice, Maurice.
Champagne.

537
00:41:51,498 --> 00:41:53,887
This is
a special occasion.

538
00:41:53,962 --> 00:41:56,002
The hotel is closing.

539
00:41:56,074 --> 00:41:58,016
You're packing.

540
00:41:58,089 --> 00:42:00,478
And the guests
are leaving.

541
00:42:00,553 --> 00:42:04,481
How often does a man
get rid of all his troubles
at the same time?

542
00:42:04,553 --> 00:42:06,822
[ Cork Pops ]

543
00:42:06,890 --> 00:42:10,272
What's the matter?
[ Screams ]

544
00:42:13,418 --> 00:42:15,327
I don't understand,
Miss Allison.

545
00:42:15,402 --> 00:42:18,566
What are you doing
in traction?

546
00:42:18,634 --> 00:42:21,122
Slipped on
a champagne cork?

547
00:42:21,194 --> 00:42:23,103
It was an accident.

548
00:42:23,178 --> 00:42:27,520
I sprung my sacroiliac.
Hmm?

549
00:42:27,593 --> 00:42:30,757
No. I've had
this happen before.

550
00:42:30,825 --> 00:42:34,884
Don't worry.
I'll be absolutely splendid
by the morning.

551
00:42:36,554 --> 00:42:39,718
The girls
can't go without her.

552
00:42:39,786 --> 00:42:43,015
You'll have to let them
stay over till tomorrow.

553
00:42:47,818 --> 00:42:50,338
[ Sighing ]

554
00:42:50,410 --> 00:42:53,574
You wouldn't think a cork
this small...

555
00:42:53,642 --> 00:42:57,155
could lay out
a woman that big.

556
00:42:57,226 --> 00:43:00,542
Now, Maria,
move Miss Fellini's luggage
into Miss Allison's room.

557
00:43:00,618 --> 00:43:02,789
Yes, sir.
Teresa and--

558
00:43:02,857 --> 00:43:06,206
Milena, sir.
Start making sandwiches.
Lots of them.

559
00:43:06,282 --> 00:43:09,032
Mr. Clavell will need
all of his strength.

560
00:43:09,098 --> 00:43:13,887
Where am I going?
On a long hike...
with the girls.

561
00:43:13,962 --> 00:43:16,962
You're going
to show them Italy...
all of it.

562
00:43:17,034 --> 00:43:19,587
And if you run out of Italy,
show them Sicily.

563
00:43:19,658 --> 00:43:21,992
That oughta take you
all day.

564
00:43:22,057 --> 00:43:24,610
And a good part
of the night, sir.

565
00:43:24,681 --> 00:43:27,648
I'm glad
we understand each other.

566
00:43:39,401 --> 00:43:42,980
It's a shame the girls
have no place to go today.

567
00:43:43,050 --> 00:43:47,425
They do.
They're going on a long hike.

568
00:43:50,090 --> 00:43:54,367
Shouldn't we offer
to go with them?

569
00:43:55,913 --> 00:44:00,136
Maurice already volunteered.
Do you want to go?

570
00:44:01,417 --> 00:44:03,621
Uh-uh.

571
00:44:16,073 --> 00:44:19,205
Hiking could never
replace this.

572
00:44:21,962 --> 00:44:26,435
Oh, Robert.

573
00:44:28,490 --> 00:44:32,102
<i>♪♪ [ Horn Honking ]</i>

574
00:44:33,898 --> 00:44:36,167
<i>♪♪ [ Honking Continues ]</i>

575
00:44:43,530 --> 00:44:45,985
<i>[ Boy ]</i>
<i>One, two, three, four.</i>
<i>Ready, set. Signals on.</i>

576
00:44:46,058 --> 00:44:48,513
<i>Hup, two, three, four.</i>
<i>Hup, two, three.</i>

577
00:44:48,586 --> 00:44:51,433
Hup, two, three, four.
Hup. Hup. Hup. Hup.

578
00:44:51,497 --> 00:44:55,687
Hey!
What's going on here?

579
00:44:55,754 --> 00:44:59,049
[ Wolf Whistle ]
Observe.

580
00:45:01,545 --> 00:45:03,618
Hey, look.
It's Barney Oldfield.

581
00:45:04,970 --> 00:45:10,153
Catch, Beagle.
Hey, two, three, four.
Hey, two, three--

582
00:45:11,657 --> 00:45:13,632
What are you
doing here?

583
00:45:13,706 --> 00:45:16,488
This is the Hotel
Dolce Vista, right?
Not anymore.

584
00:45:16,553 --> 00:45:18,757
We've got reservations.
They're cancelled.

585
00:45:18,825 --> 00:45:21,509
Hold this. I've got
written confirmation
from the manager.

586
00:45:21,578 --> 00:45:24,327
He's been cancelled too.
Sorry.

587
00:45:24,393 --> 00:45:28,136
All right, out!
Wait a minute.
Hold it.

588
00:45:29,993 --> 00:45:32,611
Beagle, you're gonna be
a lawyer, right?

589
00:45:32,681 --> 00:45:35,464
Can he do this to us?
In 1 937...

590
00:45:35,530 --> 00:45:38,312
there was the case of Wilson
versus the Waldorf Astoria.

591
00:45:38,377 --> 00:45:41,726
And?
He can do it to us.

592
00:45:41,802 --> 00:45:44,617
Good day,
gentlemen.
Yeah.

593
00:45:44,682 --> 00:45:46,591
Let's go.

594
00:45:56,361 --> 00:45:58,914
Beagle,
gimme a coin.

595
00:45:58,985 --> 00:46:01,374
Hey!

596
00:46:01,450 --> 00:46:03,654
That's for parkin'
in your driveway.

597
00:46:16,137 --> 00:46:19,366
First we end up in a stream,
then we get tossed out
of a hotel.

598
00:46:19,434 --> 00:46:23,296
This country's unlucky for us.
We could be in France
in a few hours.

599
00:46:23,370 --> 00:46:26,337
All those in favor
of leaving Italy say " aye."
[ Together] Aye!

600
00:46:30,793 --> 00:46:33,761
All those in favor
of staying in Italy say " aye."

601
00:46:33,834 --> 00:46:36,135
[ Together] Aye!
Aye!

602
00:46:37,193 --> 00:46:39,648
They're backin' up.
Don't look around.

603
00:46:39,721 --> 00:46:42,088
Which one
did you like?
I didn't notice.

604
00:46:42,153 --> 00:46:44,674
The driver was cute.
He had nice blue eyes.

605
00:46:44,746 --> 00:46:46,655
They're brown,
and keep away from him.

606
00:46:46,730 --> 00:46:48,934
[ Horn Tooting ]

607
00:46:50,858 --> 00:46:53,029
Uh... ahem, ahem.

608
00:46:53,098 --> 00:46:56,676
<i>Buon giorno.</i>
<i>Buon giorno.</i>

609
00:46:56,745 --> 00:46:59,778
This one is mine, huh?
Tell'em we want
to be friends.

610
00:46:59,849 --> 00:47:02,599
Wait a minute.
Relax. Let me handle it
and we'll all make out.

611
00:47:02,665 --> 00:47:05,054
Where do you live?

612
00:47:05,129 --> 00:47:07,398
Saus-a-lito.

613
00:47:07,465 --> 00:47:09,887
And where
is that near?

614
00:47:11,817 --> 00:47:14,981
San Fran-cis-co.

615
00:47:15,049 --> 00:47:18,213
[ All Laughing ]

616
00:47:18,281 --> 00:47:22,983
I am very stu-pid,
but I'm loads of fun.

617
00:47:23,050 --> 00:47:25,221
[ Laughing ]
Hi.

618
00:47:25,289 --> 00:47:27,972
We're from Connecticut.
Where're you girls
staying?

619
00:47:28,041 --> 00:47:30,463
Hotel La Dolce Vista.

620
00:47:30,538 --> 00:47:34,215
Isn't that a coincidence, eh?
We're staying
right outside the gate.

621
00:47:34,281 --> 00:47:36,168
But there's nothing there.

622
00:47:36,234 --> 00:47:39,168
Give us twenty minutes,
will ya? See ya.

623
00:47:39,241 --> 00:47:42,088
[ Cheering ]

624
00:47:44,105 --> 00:47:47,367
Call the police.
I want them picked up
for trespassing.

625
00:47:47,433 --> 00:47:50,215
Unfortunately, sir,
it's not your property.

626
00:47:50,282 --> 00:47:53,543
Mmm.
They're like spiders.

627
00:47:53,609 --> 00:47:56,457
And they've got
the flies helping them
put up their web!

628
00:47:56,521 --> 00:47:59,750
Why aren't those flies
out hiking?

629
00:47:59,817 --> 00:48:02,817
They insisted on going there
to help out.

630
00:48:05,290 --> 00:48:08,159
The moment I saw you,
I just seemed
to come out of my shell.

631
00:48:08,233 --> 00:48:12,772
Yes, but I think
we ought to go help
the others, Tony.

632
00:48:12,841 --> 00:48:15,808
Say that again.
What?

633
00:48:15,881 --> 00:48:20,289
My name.
Tony.

634
00:48:20,361 --> 00:48:22,336
Once more.

635
00:48:24,713 --> 00:48:26,622
Tony.

636
00:48:26,697 --> 00:48:30,439
There's something
about that boy
I don't trust.

637
00:48:30,506 --> 00:48:32,895
I don't care how you do it.
I want you--

638
00:48:32,969 --> 00:48:35,173
<i>Ciao.!</i>

639
00:48:35,241 --> 00:48:37,576
What's she doing
down there?

640
00:48:37,641 --> 00:48:39,681
Good-bye.
I'll see you later.

641
00:48:39,754 --> 00:48:41,608
<i>Ciao, ciao.</i>

642
00:48:52,234 --> 00:48:55,779
<i>♪♪ [ Lisa Humming ]</i>

643
00:48:58,025 --> 00:49:00,742
? La-la-la, la-la-la
la-la-la-la-la-la-la ?

644
00:49:00,809 --> 00:49:04,105
What were you doing
down there?
[ Laughing ]

645
00:49:04,169 --> 00:49:07,911
Darling, you're going
to be so proud of me.
I've arranged everything.

646
00:49:07,977 --> 00:49:10,727
Like what?

647
00:49:10,793 --> 00:49:12,997
? La-la-la, la-la-la
la-la ?
Like what?

648
00:49:13,065 --> 00:49:15,137
Well, first the boys
will need some kerosene.

649
00:49:15,209 --> 00:49:18,526
Why? What are they
planning to burn?
It's for their stove.

650
00:49:18,601 --> 00:49:22,017
Really, they're
very nice American boys.
So was the Dalton gang.

651
00:49:22,089 --> 00:49:25,864
The boys are very hurt.
They think you don't like them.
The boys are right.

652
00:49:25,929 --> 00:49:28,744
They're college students
on their first vacation
in Europe.

653
00:49:28,809 --> 00:49:32,006
Go make friends with them.
I don't want
to make friends with them!

654
00:49:32,073 --> 00:49:36,099
I don't understand you.
They're very sweet.
Sweet.

655
00:49:36,169 --> 00:49:38,057
Yes!
Yes.

656
00:49:38,121 --> 00:49:42,856
Do you know what the boys
are going to do with the girls
this afternoon?
No.

657
00:49:44,393 --> 00:49:47,142
What are the boys
going to do with the girls
this afternoon?

658
00:49:47,210 --> 00:49:51,366
I thought, those poor girls
have nothing to do.
Those boys have nothing to do.

659
00:49:51,433 --> 00:49:54,695
Maybe they could use
the sun terrace. But I thought,
no, Robert wouldn't like that.

660
00:49:54,761 --> 00:49:57,249
No, Robert
wouldn't like that.

661
00:49:57,321 --> 00:49:59,776
Then I said to myself,
"Wouldn't it be nice...

662
00:49:59,849 --> 00:50:04,606
if they all rented
motor scooters and went
for a ride in the country?"

663
00:50:04,681 --> 00:50:07,431
That's what you said
to yourself.
Yes!

664
00:50:07,497 --> 00:50:10,083
Did you say it to them?
Yes.
And the boys said...

665
00:50:10,153 --> 00:50:14,114
it sounded like
it would be a lot of fun.
That sounds like the boys.

666
00:50:14,185 --> 00:50:16,040
<i>- M</i>r. Clavell?
- Sir?

667
00:50:16,105 --> 00:50:19,335
You are to go with them,
and you are not to let
those girls out of your sight.

668
00:50:19,401 --> 00:50:22,783
Sir, I can't ride
a motor scooter.
Then learn.

669
00:50:22,857 --> 00:50:24,712
I have
no sense of balance.

670
00:50:24,777 --> 00:50:27,461
I was the only child
that ever had to be
strapped to his tricycle.

671
00:50:27,530 --> 00:50:30,693
I don't intend to let them go
out alone. Lisa, please!
Robert!

672
00:50:30,762 --> 00:50:34,536
I don't know how I let myself
get talked into all of this,
but I'm in it.

673
00:50:34,602 --> 00:50:37,700
It's not his hotel.
It's my home.

674
