01:07:31,560 --> 01:07:34,527
that exists between
your generation... and ours.

911
01:07:54,281 --> 01:07:56,386
Ahh.

912
01:07:56,457 --> 01:07:59,326
A-Another toast, sir.

913
01:08:01,224 --> 01:08:05,447
May these drinks
wash away the past
and ensure the future.

914
01:08:08,200 --> 01:08:10,502
To a little insurance.

915
01:08:25,352 --> 01:08:27,262
Now then.

916
01:08:50,152 --> 01:08:54,080
Sir, I'd like
to propose a toast then.

917
01:08:54,152 --> 01:08:57,982
To what?
You name it.

918
01:08:58,056 --> 01:09:00,390
Well--
How do you feel?

919
01:09:00,456 --> 01:09:02,496
Fine.

920
01:09:11,272 --> 01:09:16,291
Sir, do you realize
that you are defying
the laws of medical science?

921
01:09:19,208 --> 01:09:22,405
Dr. Lister
and Louis Pasteur...

922
01:09:22,472 --> 01:09:26,084
and, uh... Madame Curie.

923
01:09:28,968 --> 01:09:32,481
All their work, sir,
is for nothing.

924
01:09:53,800 --> 01:09:55,523
Ahh.

925
01:10:13,864 --> 01:10:16,253
[ Knock At Door]

926
01:10:21,000 --> 01:10:23,139
I'm sorry.

927
01:10:23,208 --> 01:10:26,557
Some unfinished business
I had to attend to.

928
01:10:29,480 --> 01:10:31,302
<i>[ Thudding ]</i>

929
01:10:31,368 --> 01:10:33,987
<i>Oh, Robert.!</i>

930
01:10:34,952 --> 01:10:38,814
What's wrong?
What's happened?

931
01:10:38,888 --> 01:10:41,441
I got'em.

932
01:10:41,512 --> 01:10:45,058
Every last one of'em.

933
01:10:47,496 --> 01:10:50,812
Tony? Tony!

934
01:10:52,008 --> 01:10:54,626
What happened?

935
01:10:54,696 --> 01:10:56,965
Tony!

936
01:11:13,256 --> 01:11:16,126
Tony!
Hmm?

937
01:11:31,976 --> 01:11:34,343
Uh-- [ Groans ]

938
01:11:38,728 --> 01:11:41,149
Tony?

939
01:11:43,016 --> 01:11:46,661
Are you all right?

940
01:11:46,728 --> 01:11:48,702
Of course
I'm all right.

941
01:11:48,776 --> 01:11:50,500
A little wet,
that's all.

942
01:11:50,568 --> 01:11:53,121
Come on.
Try and stand up.

943
01:11:54,248 --> 01:11:57,314
Now see
if you can walk.

944
01:11:57,384 --> 01:12:00,384
Of course
I can walk!

945
01:12:03,592 --> 01:12:06,723
Mmm.
How do
you feel?

946
01:12:06,792 --> 01:12:10,567
What happened?

947
01:12:12,520 --> 01:12:17,027
Mr. Talbot,
he called us in.

948
01:12:17,096 --> 01:12:20,609
And then he forced us
to drink with him.

949
01:12:20,680 --> 01:12:22,535
Oh, Tony.

950
01:12:22,600 --> 01:12:26,048
If I could lie down
for a minute, I'd feel fine.

951
01:12:26,119 --> 01:12:29,349
Do you want
to go in the house?

952
01:12:29,416 --> 01:12:33,278
No, I better not.
I better go back to the tent.

953
01:12:39,080 --> 01:12:41,316
Tony!
Hmm?

954
01:12:44,296 --> 01:12:46,663
Maybe I need
a little help.

955
01:12:47,976 --> 01:12:50,212
Robert!

956
01:12:50,280 --> 01:12:52,833
How could you do this?
Hmm?

957
01:12:52,903 --> 01:12:55,140
I was only following
their golden rule:

958
01:12:55,208 --> 01:12:57,696
"Do unto others before
they do it to you!"

959
01:12:57,768 --> 01:13:00,102
You can't let them
lie there all night.

960
01:13:00,168 --> 01:13:02,918
Maurice can sweep'em off
in the morning.

961
01:13:02,984 --> 01:13:06,497
Look, don't feel sorry
for them.

962
01:13:06,568 --> 01:13:09,350
They got exactly
what they deserved.

963
01:13:09,416 --> 01:13:11,489
Somebody has to look after
those girls.

964
01:13:11,560 --> 01:13:14,178
Isn't that their
parents' responsibility?

965
01:13:14,248 --> 01:13:16,615
You know the trouble
with the American parent?

966
01:13:16,680 --> 01:13:20,608
They have a new gimmick:
Keep your kids
off the streets.

967
01:13:20,680 --> 01:13:22,819
Send them to Europe!

968
01:13:22,888 --> 01:13:27,394
They're turning this
continent into one big
corner drugstore!

969
01:13:32,136 --> 01:13:34,023
It's gone!

970
01:13:34,088 --> 01:13:36,902
What?
There's
a body missing.

971
01:13:36,968 --> 01:13:41,059
It's the one body
I don't wanna have missing.

972
01:13:44,743 --> 01:13:47,743
Sandy, wait.
I was drunk, I swear.
I didn't know what I was doing.

973
01:13:47,816 --> 01:13:51,013
The next time I see a man
lying in a bar,
I'll leave him there!

974
01:13:51,080 --> 01:13:53,665
Mr. Talbot, did you force
him to drink with you?
Of course not.

975
01:13:53,735 --> 01:13:55,743
And that's for lying!

976
01:13:55,816 --> 01:13:59,231
Sandy, honey--
Sandy?

977
01:14:02,312 --> 01:14:04,614
Thank you.

978
01:14:04,680 --> 01:14:09,186
You've reaffirmed
my lack of confidence
in my fellow man.

979
01:14:24,359 --> 01:14:26,781
Sandy.
Hmm?

980
01:14:26,856 --> 01:14:29,092
Are you all right?

981
01:14:29,159 --> 01:14:31,331
Sure!
He's cute, isn't he?

982
01:14:31,400 --> 01:14:33,255
Who?
Tony!

983
01:14:33,320 --> 01:14:37,095
I hope I didn't loosen any
of his teeth when I hit him.
He has a beautiful smile!

984
01:14:37,160 --> 01:14:40,989
You're not mad at him?
Mad at him?
Why would I be mad?

985
01:14:41,064 --> 01:14:42,919
Wait, wait.

986
01:14:42,984 --> 01:14:46,530
He got fresh.
You hit him.
Mm-hmm.

987
01:14:46,600 --> 01:14:49,382
But you're not mad.
You like him!
Oh, I adore him!

988
01:14:49,448 --> 01:14:51,652
<i>E gia figure.!</i>

989
01:14:51,720 --> 01:14:55,364
The business the psychiatrists
must do in America.

990
01:14:55,431 --> 01:14:58,628
You people are...
all mixed up.

991
01:14:58,696 --> 01:15:02,012
You see, when he got fresh,
it showed that
he was interested.

992
01:15:02,088 --> 01:15:04,674
I had to make sure
he stayed interested.
So you hit him.

993
01:15:04,744 --> 01:15:06,784
That's right.

994
01:15:06,855 --> 01:15:09,190
It's like
Mr. Talbot said.

995
01:15:09,256 --> 01:15:12,103
A girl has to make a boy
respect her.

996
01:15:12,168 --> 01:15:16,423
If she gives in too easily,
he'll never
take her seriously.

997
01:15:16,488 --> 01:15:18,943
Oh.

998
01:15:19,016 --> 01:15:21,187
He said that?
Mm-hmm.

999
01:15:21,255 --> 01:15:24,419
And he's right.
He said, " When you
go shopping in a market,

1000
01:15:24,487 --> 01:15:27,553
you don't buy anything
that's been handled
too much."

1001
01:15:27,624 --> 01:15:32,926
Oh. When did Mr. Talbot
tell you all this?

1002
01:15:33,032 --> 01:15:35,039
While we were dancing.
He said,

1003
01:15:35,112 --> 01:15:38,373
"If you want a man to think
in terms of getting
engaged and married,

1004
01:15:38,440 --> 01:15:42,368
<i>then you've got to keep</i>
<i>your standards high. "</i>

1005
01:15:42,440 --> 01:15:45,058
Hmm. What else
did he say?

1006
01:15:45,128 --> 01:15:50,496
He said that love is
one product you don't sell
by giving away free samples.

1007
01:15:52,104 --> 01:15:54,526
Hmm.

1008
01:15:54,599 --> 01:15:57,414
That's good advice
for all of us.

1009
01:15:58,952 --> 01:16:03,807
You listen to him.
I can tell you he knows
what he's talking about.

1010
01:16:03,880 --> 01:16:06,019
I know.

1011
01:16:09,543 --> 01:16:12,478
Well?

1012
01:16:13,928 --> 01:16:18,019
[ Chuckles ]
I guess you learned
something tonight, huh?

1013
01:16:18,087 --> 01:16:22,528
Yes! I never realized
how wrong I was.

1014
01:16:22,600 --> 01:16:25,185
Oh, it's all
in the past now.

1015
01:16:25,256 --> 01:16:28,071
You're so right.

1016
01:16:28,136 --> 01:16:31,038
It's been a long day.

1017
01:16:31,112 --> 01:16:35,968
Some champagne would
do us both a world of good.
Mm-hmm.

1018
01:16:36,039 --> 01:16:39,269
The bottle's on the terrace.
I'll go get it, huh?

1019
01:16:39,336 --> 01:16:41,703
Mm-hmm.

1020
01:16:41,768 --> 01:16:43,677
Robert?
Hmm?

1021
01:16:43,751 --> 01:16:47,810
- When you get to the terrace,
would you do me a favor?
- Sure!

1022
01:16:47,880 --> 01:16:50,629
Jump off!

1023
01:16:51,591 --> 01:16:53,479
<i>[ Door Slams ]</i>

1024
01:17:00,968 --> 01:17:03,717
What are you doing?
Taking your advice.

1025
01:17:03,784 --> 01:17:09,315
If a woman's too easy
to get, the man will never
take her seriously. Hmm?

1026
01:17:09,383 --> 01:17:12,285
When I think
how easy I was!

1027
01:17:12,359 --> 01:17:14,498
<i>Stupida.! Cretina.!</i>
<i>Idiota.!</i>

1028
01:17:14,568 --> 01:17:18,496
It's something I told some
impressionable young girls.
To protect their morals.

1029
01:17:18,567 --> 01:17:22,822
What about my morals?
What's that got to do
with it? We're adults.

1030
01:17:22,888 --> 01:17:25,735
Lisa, look,
if you'll just calm down.

1031
01:17:25,799 --> 01:17:28,036
Don't touch me!

1032
01:17:28,968 --> 01:17:31,390
How could I be
that stupid?

1033
01:17:33,448 --> 01:17:37,572
You're wealthy, good-looking,
intelligent, charming!

1034
01:17:37,640 --> 01:17:41,862
I should have known better
than to get mixed up
with someone like that.

1035
01:17:41,927 --> 01:17:45,440
You're not making any sense.
I don't have to.
I'm Italian!

1036
01:17:45,511 --> 01:17:48,740
<i>Ci sono dei uomini</i>
<i>molto piu interessante</i>
<i>di te qui in Italia.</i>

1037
01:17:48,808 --> 01:17:51,742
<i>Cosa credi.!</i>
<i>Sono stufa dei America.</i>
<i>Stufa.!</i>

1038
01:17:51,815 --> 01:17:54,565
Talk English.
I can't understand you!
Ahh!

1039
01:17:54,632 --> 01:17:58,855
That's another thing!
If you loved me, you'd have
learned my language!

1040
01:17:58,920 --> 01:18:01,254
But no!
I had to do it.

1041
01:18:01,319 --> 01:18:04,036
The weeks
I spent studying!

1042
01:18:04,103 --> 01:18:09,341
Learning to speak this...
"fluid" English!
Not fluid, fluent!

1043
01:18:09,415 --> 01:18:13,092
Big shot!
Knows all the words!

1044
01:18:13,160 --> 01:18:16,607
For the first time
I started to think,
"What am I doing here?"

1045
01:18:16,679 --> 01:18:20,421
Lisa, believe me.
No love affair can survive
if either party starts to think.

1046
01:18:20,488 --> 01:18:22,854
That's been the beauty
of our relationship.
No thinking.

1047
01:18:22,920 --> 01:18:24,807
No pressure.
No questions asked.

1048
01:18:24,871 --> 01:18:28,133
It's time someone
started asking questions.

1049
01:18:28,199 --> 01:18:30,720
I knew those girls
would get me in trouble!

1050
01:18:30,792 --> 01:18:35,876
You're a hypocrite.
You made all the rules
and I played by them.

1051
01:18:35,943 --> 01:18:38,758
Now I know what
you think of me.
Lisa.

1052
01:18:38,823 --> 01:18:41,791
Well, the game is over,
Robert.

1053
01:18:41,864 --> 01:18:44,482
I don't want
to play anymore.
If you'll calm--

1054
01:18:44,552 --> 01:18:48,130
I'm tired of being
a free sample.

1055
01:18:48,199 --> 01:18:51,494
There's no future in it.
<i>We've never talked</i>
<i>about the future.</i>

1056
01:18:51,560 --> 01:18:55,171
Women don't want talk.
They go by intuition.

1057
01:18:55,239 --> 01:19:00,061
And I've learned one thing.
A woman's intuition
is a man's best friend.

1058
01:19:00,135 --> 01:19:03,681
Lisa, wait.
The market's closed.

1059
01:19:03,752 --> 01:19:06,686
You'll have to start shopping
somewhere else.

1060
01:19:09,512 --> 01:19:11,781
Lisa?

1061
01:19:11,847 --> 01:19:13,734
Lisa!

1062
01:19:25,416 --> 01:19:27,204
[ Hiccups ]

1063
01:19:38,471 --> 01:19:40,893
Who's in that tent?

1064
01:19:40,967 --> 01:19:44,644
Boys.
Boys?

1065
01:19:57,991 --> 01:20:00,413
Watch your head,
my dear.

1066
01:20:03,431 --> 01:20:05,765
Did my girls meet them?

1067
01:20:05,831 --> 01:20:08,766
Meet whom?
Those boys in the tent?

1068
01:20:08,839 --> 01:20:10,694
Oh, those boys.
Yes.
What?

1069
01:20:10,759 --> 01:20:13,923
But the boys
weren't interested
in feminine companionship.

1070
01:20:13,991 --> 01:20:17,439
They're too absorbed
by the educational aspects
of their tour.

1071
01:20:17,512 --> 01:20:19,715
It's too bad you won't
have time to meet them.

1072
01:20:19,784 --> 01:20:22,686
They're such fine, clean-cut
American gentlemen.

1073
01:20:22,759 --> 01:20:26,436
True goodwill ambassadors
of a great nation.

1074
01:20:29,448 --> 01:20:31,422
Which way is the tent?

1075
01:20:31,495 --> 01:20:33,732
What happened
to the girls?
I don't know.

1076
01:20:33,799 --> 01:20:36,832
Man, what a night.

1077
01:20:36,903 --> 01:20:39,653
Maurice!
I assure you, my dear,
I'm as shocked as you are.

1078
01:20:39,719 --> 01:20:42,086
If anything's happened
to those girls--

1079
01:20:46,407 --> 01:20:49,255
Margaret,
believe me, please.

1080
01:20:49,319 --> 01:20:52,548
Nothing happened.
Absolutely nothing!
I'm sure.

1081
01:20:52,615 --> 01:20:56,260
I sincerely hope not.
Remember, I left those girls
in your care.

1082
01:20:57,992 --> 01:21:01,221
Oh, Cedric!

1083
01:21:01,287 --> 01:21:03,327
[ Hiccups ]

1084
01:21:04,871 --> 01:21:06,846
He hiccupped.

1085
01:21:06,919 --> 01:21:08,610
[ Chuckles ]
He did.

1086
01:21:10,247 --> 01:21:12,352
[ Burps ]

1087
01:21:13,031 --> 01:21:14,919
Cedric!

1088
01:21:18,119 --> 01:21:20,006
He's drunk!

1089
01:21:22,440 --> 01:21:26,596
Maurice, what kind of a party
did you have here last night?

1090
01:21:26,663 --> 01:21:29,533
<i>[ Talbot ]</i>
<i>Lisa, come back here.</i>

1091
01:21:29,607 --> 01:21:32,836
I said don't touch me!
If you'd wait,
everybody will be gone.

1092
01:21:32,904 --> 01:21:36,199
We can talk like adults.
I don't want to talk
like an adult.

1093
01:21:36,263 --> 01:21:38,270
That's how I got
into all this trouble.

1094
01:21:38,343 --> 01:21:41,377
How are you going to get
back? There's no train.
I'll walk!

1095
01:21:41,448 --> 01:21:43,684
You're very welcome
to come with us.
Thank you.

1096
01:21:43,751 --> 01:21:46,020
You keep out of this!

1097
01:21:46,088 --> 01:21:49,732
<i>Lisa, don't you</i>
<i>walk out that door.</i>

1098
01:21:49,799 --> 01:21:54,884
Oh, what would I lose?
The privilege of seeing you
every September?

1099
01:21:54,951 --> 01:21:57,951
Well, I'm tired of being
"girl of the month."

1100
01:21:58,023 --> 01:22:01,820
You know
you're more than that.
Oh, don't worry, Robert.

1101
01:22:01,895 --> 01:22:05,343
You won't have any trouble.
Just put an ad in the paper.

1102
01:22:05,415 --> 01:22:09,954
"Girl wanted. Short hours.
Pleasant working conditions."

1103
01:22:10,023 --> 01:22:14,813
There's only one drawback.
There's no chance
of advancement.

1104
01:22:16,167 --> 01:22:19,266
Wild parties!
Immoral rendezvous!

1105
01:22:19,336 --> 01:22:21,791
And to think
I trusted you!

1106
01:22:21,864 --> 01:22:24,253
The next think I'll find out
this isn't even an hotel.

1107
01:22:24,327 --> 01:22:28,419
That's precisely the next thing
you're about to find out.
Sir?

1108
01:22:28,488 --> 01:22:32,448
You, you're fired.
And you, madam,
take those girls of yours,

1109
01:22:32,519 --> 01:22:36,797
[ Hiccups ]
pack that drunken bird
and get out!

1110
01:22:36,872 --> 01:22:39,871
Are you going to allow him
to speak to me like that?

1111
01:22:39,943 --> 01:22:44,002
Margaret, there's
a small detail I should
have mentioned before.

1112
01:22:44,071 --> 01:22:47,333
I know you're going to take
this with your customary
good sense of humor.

1113
01:22:47,399 --> 01:22:49,701
Margaret, listen to me.
[ Car Horn Honks ]

1114
01:22:49,767 --> 01:22:52,898
Where's that good sense
of humor? Margaret?

1115
01:22:53,927 --> 01:22:56,415
Margaret?

1116
01:23:01,159 --> 01:23:03,680
Sandy, honey, listen.

1117
01:23:04,775 --> 01:23:07,775
Hey, Sandy?

1118
01:23:18,439 --> 01:23:20,294
I'm packed, sir.

1119
01:23:20,359 --> 01:23:23,655
Good-bye,
Mr. Clavell.

1120
01:23:23,719 --> 01:23:27,297
Before I leave, can I
get you some breakfast?
No. Yes, get me an olive.

1121
01:23:27,431 --> 01:23:29,853
A martini for breakfast?

1122
01:23:29,928 --> 01:23:34,662
It's great for the morning after--
especially if there
hasn't been a night before.

1123
01:23:34,728 --> 01:23:38,339
Yes, sir.
Oh, before I forget.

1124
01:23:38,407 --> 01:23:41,058
Would you kindly sign this,
sir?
What is it?

1125
01:23:41,127 --> 01:23:43,232
It's a letter
of recommendation.

1126
01:23:43,303 --> 01:23:46,652
A letter
of recommendation?

1127
01:23:46,727 --> 01:23:50,043
I didn't want to trouble
you, so I took the liberty
of writing it myself.

1128
01:23:50,119 --> 01:23:52,989
Just sign here.

1129
01:23:53,063 --> 01:23:56,544
It's much too trivial
for you to bother reading.

1130
01:23:59,271 --> 01:24:01,955
"Loyal.

1131
01:24:02,023 --> 01:24:05,765
<i>"Faithful. Dedicated.</i>
<i>Noble.</i>

1132
01:24:05,831 --> 01:24:08,701
Reputable.
Incorruptible."

1133
01:24:08,775 --> 01:24:11,623
It does get
rather monotonous.

1134
01:24:15,271 --> 01:24:18,304
"Nearly saint-like
in his devotion to his master."

1135
01:24:18,375 --> 01:24:20,863
Yes, sir.

1136
01:24:22,471 --> 01:24:25,505
Anybody that believes this
deserves you.

1137
01:24:28,551 --> 01:24:32,544
Thank you very much, sir.
I'll get the olive.

1138
01:24:40,775 --> 01:24:44,157
May I speak to you
a moment, sir?

1139
01:24:44,231 --> 01:24:46,784
Well, if it isn't
the prowling physician!

1140
01:24:48,711 --> 01:24:51,078
I don't blame you, sir.

1141
01:24:51,143 --> 01:24:53,729
After the way I acted
with Sandy last night,

1142
01:24:53,799 --> 01:24:55,905
I'm no credit
to the medical profession.
Hardly.

1143
01:24:55,976 --> 01:24:58,245
I came to apologize,
sir.

1144
01:24:58,311 --> 01:25:01,311
<i>No gimmicks this time.</i>

1145
01:25:01,383 --> 01:25:04,230
You had us pegged
right from the beginning.

1146
01:25:04,295 --> 01:25:07,426
That's probably
why we got so sore at you.

1147
01:25:07,496 --> 01:25:09,634
Sir, do you know
what a lemming is?

1148
01:25:09,703 --> 01:25:11,613
No.

1149
01:25:11,687 --> 01:25:14,786
<i>It's an animal</i>
<i>that destroys itself.</i>
Huh.

1150
01:25:14,855 --> 01:25:19,973
I've gotta look up
my family tree, 'cause there
must've been some real lemmings.

1151
01:25:20,039 --> 01:25:24,261
I meet a great girl like Sandy,
and what do I do?
I goof the whole thing up.

1152
01:25:24,327 --> 01:25:26,465
I acted just like
a stupid adolescent.

1153
01:25:26,535 --> 01:25:29,318
I'm not a kid anymore.
I know better than that.

1154
01:25:29,383 --> 01:25:32,678
I'm getting on in years.
You're not
exactly ancient.

1155
01:25:32,743 --> 01:25:36,769
No, but when a guy gets to be
as old as I am, you'd think
he'd be smart enough...

1156
01:25:36,839 --> 01:25:40,800
to stop fooling around
and start looking
for a lasting relationship.

1157
01:25:40,871 --> 01:25:45,541
Look, once in a while,
if you're lucky, you come across
something of real value.

1158
01:25:45,607 --> 01:25:48,324
And what do you do with it?
You treat it just like
a bargain basement special.

1159
01:25:48,391 --> 01:25:51,108
You start grabbing it,
and then you lose it.

1160
01:25:51,175 --> 01:25:56,358
<i>And you spend the rest of</i>
<i>your life shopping around for</i>
<i>something not half as good.</i>

1161
01:26:01,159 --> 01:26:05,665
Anyhow...
I came by to say I'm sorry.

1162
01:26:07,687 --> 01:26:10,785
<i>So long, Mr. Talbot.</i>
Uh, Tony!

1163
01:26:16,263 --> 01:26:17,986
Yes, sir?

1164
01:26:22,023 --> 01:26:24,226
Have a nice trip.

1165
01:26:26,343 --> 01:26:29,409
Thank you, sir.
Thank you.

1166
01:26:37,831 --> 01:26:39,686
Here you are, sir.

1167
01:26:39,751 --> 01:26:43,875
Mr. Clavell,
I just learned something.

1168
01:26:44,903 --> 01:26:47,751
I'm a lemming.

1169
01:26:47,815 --> 01:26:51,361
You really should have
something more substantial
for breakfast, sir.

1170
01:26:51,431 --> 01:26:55,107
Man is the only animal
clever enough to build
the Empire State Building,

1171
01:26:55,175 --> 01:26:57,989
and stupid enough
to jump off it.

1172
01:26:58,055 --> 01:27:00,422
Get the car, Maurice.

1173
01:27:00,487 --> 01:27:03,105
[ Chuckling ]
Yes, sir!

1174
01:27:07,847 --> 01:27:10,214
I don't see them.

1175
01:27:10,279 --> 01:27:14,534
Sparrow, stop worrying!
He'll follow us.

1176
01:27:14,599 --> 01:27:17,316
Who?
Tony!

1177
01:27:17,383 --> 01:27:21,573
You don't think I'd've left
if I didn't think
he was gonna come after me!

1178
01:27:21,639 --> 01:27:25,316
Don't you worry,
'cause Mr. Talbot
will come after you too.

1179
01:27:26,407 --> 01:27:29,603
Believe me, Sandy,
I couldn't care less.

1180
01:27:43,943 --> 01:27:48,580
A <i>$</i>20,000 car isn't
supposed to get a flat!

1181
01:27:48,647 --> 01:27:52,029
Evidently the manufacturers
felt the same way.
Huh?

1182
01:27:52,103 --> 01:27:54,525
There's no jack
to change the tire.

1183
01:27:54,599 --> 01:27:58,243
Oh. There must be
a garage around here someplace.

1184
01:27:58,311 --> 01:28:03,046
<i>Hey, va via.! Va via.!</i>
<i>Dove ha il garagio</i>
<i>il piu viccino?</i>

1185
01:28:03,111 --> 01:28:05,926
They don't know.
I'll ask inside.

1186
01:28:05,991 --> 01:28:08,708
<i>[ Geese Quacking ]</i>

1187
01:28:21,351 --> 01:28:24,068
You there,
I want to borrow your truck.

1188
01:28:24,135 --> 01:28:28,292
<i>Mi dispiace</i>
<i>ma non vi capisco.</i>
I want to borrow your truck.

1189
01:28:28,359 --> 01:28:31,654
I'll pay you for it.
<i>Non, ma non posso.</i>

1190
01:28:31,719 --> 01:28:34,916
It's an emergency.
I'll buy it! Here!

1191
01:28:34,983 --> 01:28:38,595
<i>Mi scusa, ma questo carro</i>
<i>non e miga mio.</i>

1192
01:28:38,663 --> 01:28:41,827
<i>Perche mi ha datto</i>
<i>questo denaro?</i>
<i>Non e mio.</i>

1193
01:28:46,022 --> 01:28:47,877
Get in.

1194
01:28:47,942 --> 01:28:49,731
There's a garage--
Never mind.
Get in.

1195
01:28:49,799 --> 01:28:51,872
In this?
Yes!

1196
01:29:07,495 --> 01:29:10,878
[ Speaking Italian ]

1197
01:29:10,951 --> 01:29:13,372
<i>Va bene. Va bene.</i>
[ Speaking Italian ]

1198
01:29:13,447 --> 01:29:15,520
<i>Il mio carro.!</i>

1199
01:29:15,591 --> 01:29:18,274
<i>Ma come,</i>
<i>quelle se n'e andato.!</i>
<i>Era qui adesso.!</i>

1200
01:29:18,343 --> 01:29:20,415
<i>Fermati.!</i>
<i>Fermati.!</i>

1201
01:29:20,486 --> 01:29:24,643
<i>Calmati figlio mio.!</i>
<i>Chiamiamo la polizia. Adesso.</i>

1202
01:29:24,711 --> 01:29:27,133
<i>Eh, bisogna</i>
<i>pure fare qualcosa.</i>

1203
01:29:27,206 --> 01:29:30,818
[ Geese Quacking ]

1204
01:29:30,887 --> 01:29:33,789
There they are, sir.

1205
01:29:40,519 --> 01:29:44,414
[ Quacking ]

1206
01:29:44,486 --> 01:29:48,229
Here!
Take this bird.
Take the wheel.

1207
01:29:52,039 --> 01:29:54,111
Lisa?
What?

1208
01:29:54,182 --> 01:29:57,663
Lisa, stop the bus.
I want to talk to you.

1209
01:29:57,735 --> 01:30:00,190
Go away!

1210
01:30:00,263 --> 01:30:02,335
I've been thinking.

1211
01:30:02,407 --> 01:30:06,236
You want me
to take you seriously?
Okay, I take you seriously!

1212
01:30:06,310 --> 01:30:08,547
It's too late.

1213
01:30:08,615 --> 01:30:11,135
What do you want me to do,
marry you?

1214
01:30:11,207 --> 01:30:13,117
Okay, I'll marry you!

1215
01:30:13,190 --> 01:30:15,579
You sound like
you do me a favor.

1216
01:30:15,655 --> 01:30:18,273
I'm not doing you any favor
by marrying you.

1217
01:30:18,342 --> 01:30:21,441
If you asked me
when we first met,

1218
01:30:21,511 --> 01:30:23,933
or last year,
or even yesterday.

1219
01:30:24,007 --> 01:30:27,552
We never spoke of marriage.
We were happy.

1220
01:30:27,623 --> 01:30:32,227
Mmm. I'll always feel
I forced you into it.

1221
01:30:32,295 --> 01:30:34,596
[ Shouting ]
Do I sound like
I'm being forced?

1222
01:30:34,662 --> 01:30:37,761
You don't seem happy
about it!

1223
01:30:37,831 --> 01:30:40,002
I've never been happier!

1224
01:30:40,070 --> 01:30:42,918
Look, dammit!
I'm smiling!

1225
01:30:42,983 --> 01:30:45,798
It would never work.

1226
01:30:45,863 --> 01:30:51,133
Lisa, I'm asking you
in a nice way.

1227
01:30:51,207 --> 01:30:53,727
Now stop being an idiot!

1228
01:30:53,799 --> 01:30:58,142
Get off that blasted bus
and marry me!

1229
01:30:58,215 --> 01:30:59,840
No!

1230
01:31:00,967 --> 01:31:05,440
Okay. Don't ever say
I never asked you.

1231
01:31:07,783 --> 01:31:10,565
You're a witness.
You heard me ask her.

1232
01:31:14,407 --> 01:31:18,563
Don't stop now, sir.
Follow them.
No, Maurice.

1233
01:31:25,542 --> 01:31:29,187
I'm like this goose.
I know when
I've laid an egg.

1234
01:31:31,495 --> 01:31:34,790
I want that villa
put up for sale.

1235
01:31:34,855 --> 01:31:38,270
And if you can't sell it,
burn it! I've had it
with this country!

1236
01:31:38,343 --> 01:31:40,830
Sir, this is no time
to be burning your villas
behind you.

1237
01:31:40,902 --> 01:31:44,677
She wants to marry you.
Yeah, she has
a funny way of showing it.

1238
01:31:44,742 --> 01:31:47,044
Italian women are emotional.

1239
01:31:47,110 --> 01:31:49,728
Sh-She's been hurt.
She wants time to think.

1240
01:31:49,798 --> 01:31:51,937
Well, I wanna
go back to America...

1241
01:31:52,007 --> 01:31:55,041
where people get married
without thinking.

1242
01:31:55,111 --> 01:31:59,234
<i>Ecco-lo li.!</i>
<i>Arrestate-lo.!</i>

1243
01:31:59,303 --> 01:32:01,888
[ Whistles Blowing ]

1244
01:32:01,959 --> 01:32:03,715
<i>Ferma.!</i>

1245
01:32:03,782 --> 01:32:06,116
<i>Ferma, ferma.!</i>

1246
01:32:07,495 --> 01:32:11,040
<i>Arrestate-lo.</i>
<i>E lui che a preso</i>
<i>la machina.!</i>

1247
01:32:11,110 --> 01:32:12,834
[ Shouting In Italian ]

1248
01:32:12,903 --> 01:32:16,285
<i>Arrestate-lo.</i>
<i>Va bene.</i>

1249
01:32:16,359 --> 01:32:18,726
<i>E dunque.!</i>
What are they saying?

1250
01:32:18,790 --> 01:32:21,757
They say you stole
his truck.
His truck?

1251
01:32:21,830 --> 01:32:26,533
<i>That's ridiculous.</i>
<i>I bought it.</i>
<i>I paid a man $600 for it.</i>

1252
01:32:32,263 --> 01:32:35,012
I never stole anything
in my life.

1253
01:32:38,662 --> 01:32:40,288
Tell him that's my car
over there.

1254
01:32:41,894 --> 01:32:45,211
<i>Quella? Giu.! Giu.!</i>

1255
01:32:46,982 --> 01:32:50,146
I resent being treated
as though I were
a member of the Mafia!

1256
01:32:56,902 --> 01:32:59,717
What are they doing?

1257
01:32:59,782 --> 01:33:01,725
Maurice,
tell them who I am.

1258
01:33:05,894 --> 01:33:07,301
That's right.

1259
01:33:15,078 --> 01:33:18,559
Mm-hmm. They probably
want some money.
Offer them a bribe.

1260
01:33:18,630 --> 01:33:19,743
<i>Che dice?</i>

1261
01:33:22,279 --> 01:33:24,166
<i>La forte taglia?</i>

1262
01:33:29,703 --> 01:33:32,223
<i>E sicura?</i>
<i>Certo.</i>

1263
01:33:43,111 --> 01:33:45,183
<i>E giusto.!</i>
<i>Io lo Portero.</i>

1264
01:33:45,254 --> 01:33:48,637
<i>No. Lo portiamo a Roma.</i>
<i>E quello che volevo dire.</i>
<i>Lo portiamo a--</i>

1265
01:33:48,711 --> 01:33:53,348
<i>No.! Lo portiamo tutti tre.</i>
<i>Io, te e lui.</i>

1266
01:33:53,415 --> 01:33:55,073
<i>A l'ordine, brigadier.</i>

1267
01:33:55,142 --> 01:33:57,531
Did you tell'em
about the money?

1268
01:33:57,607 --> 01:34:00,160
Yes, sir. They're
definitely interested.

1269
01:34:00,231 --> 01:34:02,686
The time I wasted on him!

1270
01:34:02,759 --> 01:34:05,312
On a hypocrite,
a liar, a fraud!

1271
01:34:05,383 --> 01:34:09,060
And you are fortunate.
Most women don't find it out
till after they are married.

1272
01:34:09,127 --> 01:34:11,615
I'm lucky to get
a man like Spencer.

1273
01:34:11,686 --> 01:34:16,476
He's honest, uh...
sincere, sympathetic and...

1274
01:34:16,551 --> 01:34:18,438
reliable!

1275
01:34:18,502 --> 01:34:20,412
Everything Robert isn't.

1276
01:34:20,487 --> 01:34:23,716
But at least Robert
did me one favor.

1277
01:34:23,783 --> 01:34:28,420
He did?
He asked me to marry him.
He begged me.

1278
01:34:28,487 --> 01:34:32,262
And that freed me
of him forever!

1279
01:34:32,327 --> 01:34:34,498
Now I know I can be happy
with Spencer.

1280
01:34:40,166 --> 01:34:43,712
Where are they taking us?
We've been riding for hours.

1281
01:34:43,783 --> 01:34:45,343
I wish I knew, sir.

1282
01:34:45,415 --> 01:34:48,448
I don't understand it.
They act like I'm a criminal
or something.

1283
01:34:48,518 --> 01:34:50,428
I've noticed that, sir.

1284
01:34:50,503 --> 01:34:52,445
Hey!

1285
01:34:54,247 --> 01:34:59,036
Tell him I'd like to explain
everything very carefully.

1286
01:34:59,110 --> 01:35:01,314
Yes, sir.

1287
01:35:04,551 --> 01:35:06,623
Ahh!

1288
01:35:06,694 --> 01:35:09,149
There's this girl,
Lisa Fellini.

1289
01:35:12,262 --> 01:35:14,237
Tell'em
she was my houseguest.

1290
01:35:17,191 --> 01:35:18,816
<i>Complice.!</i>

1291
01:35:18,886 --> 01:35:22,629
And she lives here in Rome.
Via Bellagio, 46.

1292
01:35:26,183 --> 01:35:28,223
<i>Via Bellagio,</i>
<i>quaranta-sei.</i>
<i>Subito.</i>

1293
01:35:28,295 --> 01:35:31,393
We had an argument,
a lovers' quarrel,

1294
01:35:31,462 --> 01:35:33,983
and I was just trying
to keep her from leaving.

1295
01:35:36,391 --> 01:35:38,627
<i>Taglia.!</i>

1296
01:35:39,590 --> 01:35:40,997
Hey!

1297
01:35:41,062 --> 01:35:43,234
Agh!

1298
01:35:45,927 --> 01:35:49,058
Oh, if I only had
my lawyer here.

1299
01:35:49,127 --> 01:35:52,640
Believe me, sir,
what I'm doing for you
no lawyer could ever do.

1300
01:36:03,015 --> 01:36:07,521
You didn't see Lisa at her best.
Once you get to know her,
you'll love her.

1301
01:36:07,590 --> 01:36:11,235
She's really a shy, gentle girl,
very quiet, well-bred,
and home-loving.

1302
01:36:11,303 --> 01:36:12,961
<i>[ Policeman ]</i>
Ecco! Venga.

1303
01:36:13,030 --> 01:36:15,713
<i>Lasciatemi.</i>
<i>Non posso andare con lei.</i>

1304
01:36:15,782 --> 01:36:20,736
<i>Venga.!</i>
<i>Malscalzone.!</i>

1305
01:36:20,807 --> 01:36:25,858
[ Shouting In Italian ]

1306
01:36:25,926 --> 01:36:29,057
[ Italian ]

1307
01:36:30,214 --> 01:36:32,036
[ Screaming ]

1308
01:36:35,430 --> 01:36:37,121
[ Honks ]

1309
01:36:39,143 --> 01:36:41,892
I don't like making
snap decisions, Spencer,

1310
01:36:41,958 --> 01:36:44,675
but do you really think
this is the right girl for you?

1311
01:36:49,703 --> 01:36:51,459
Robert!

1312
01:36:55,846 --> 01:36:57,537
<i>Signorina.!</i>

1313
01:36:57,606 --> 01:36:59,613
[ Gasps ]

1314
01:37:02,470 --> 01:37:05,699
There's this man I met
about eight months ago.

1315
01:37:05,798 --> 01:37:08,897
<i>Spencer. He's been very nice</i>
<i>to me, and--</i>

1316
01:37:13,799 --> 01:37:19,515
I don't want to sue anybody
for false arrest.
I just want to get out of here.

1317
01:37:19,590 --> 01:37:22,492
If there's a plane,
a train or a bus or a jackass
leaving this city,

1318
01:37:22,566 --> 01:37:24,454
get me on it!

1319
01:37:24,519 --> 01:37:27,683
There's a train leaving
for Milan in an hour.
Fine. Get me a taxi.

1320
01:37:27,751 --> 01:37:30,882
Taxi!
Let me tell you something
about Italian women.

1321
01:37:30,950 --> 01:37:34,845
They're not to be trusted.
They're deceitful.
They're emotionally unstable.

1322
01:37:34,919 --> 01:37:37,253
Doesn't that apply
to all women?
Of course it does!

1323
01:37:37,318 --> 01:37:42,053
That's where they've got us.
We have nothing else
to replace'em with.

1324
01:37:44,519 --> 01:37:47,104
The least you can do
is go to the station
and apologize.

1325
01:37:47,174 --> 01:37:50,273
I'll write to them.
<i>Cafone.!</i>

1326
01:37:50,342 --> 01:37:52,676
First you say you don't
love me, then you spend
two nights in a man's villa.

1327
01:37:52,742 --> 01:37:55,459
Finally when you return,
you're arrested.
Oh, well--

1328
01:37:55,526 --> 01:37:58,210
Frankly, Lisa,
I can't allow this to go on
after we're married.

1329
01:37:58,278 --> 01:38:00,863
Come along.

1330
01:38:00,934 --> 01:38:05,474
<i>[ Phone Ringing ]</i>

1331
01:38:08,006 --> 01:38:09,665
Hello?

1332
01:38:12,486 --> 01:38:14,755
Yes, Maurice.

1333
01:38:16,262 --> 01:38:20,517
I don't care what train
Mr. Talbot is taking...

1334
01:38:20,582 --> 01:38:23,168
as long as he takes it.

1335
01:38:23,238 --> 01:38:25,889
We don't want him
here in Italy!

1336
01:38:25,959 --> 01:38:28,195
I speak
for the government!
Good-bye.

1337
01:38:28,262 --> 01:38:32,703
Hello?
Take care of yourself,
Maurice, huh?

1338
01:38:32,775 --> 01:38:34,978
<i>Ciao.</i>

1339
01:38:35,047 --> 01:38:37,413
<i>[ Doorbell Buzzes ]</i>

1340
01:38:38,439 --> 01:38:40,708
<i>What are you</i>
<i>so happy about?</i>

1341
01:38:40,774 --> 01:38:43,774
Lisa, I have
to talk to you.

1342
01:38:43,847 --> 01:38:46,214
Come in.

1343
01:38:47,622 --> 01:38:51,878
What's wrong?
He didn't follow me!

1344
01:38:51,942 --> 01:38:56,219
I'm going home tomorrow
and he doesn't even have
my phone number.

1345
01:38:56,294 --> 01:38:58,433
I know I'll never
see him again.
Don't worry.

1346
01:38:58,502 --> 01:39:00,476
Lisa, I don't want
to lose him.

1347
01:39:00,550 --> 01:39:04,674
I'm 1 8 and I may never
have another chance.
Of course you will.

1348
01:39:04,742 --> 01:39:07,164
No, I'm gonna
end up like you.

1349
01:39:07,239 --> 01:39:11,035
Marrying the wrong man
and miserable with someone
I don't love.

1350
01:39:11,110 --> 01:39:15,169
Nonsense.
I'm very happy with Spencer.

1351
01:39:15,238 --> 01:39:19,264
Now, listen.
Do you know where
the boys were going?

1352
01:39:19,334 --> 01:39:22,683
Yes, but what good is it?
It's like Mr. Talbot said.

1353
01:39:22,758 --> 01:39:26,336
It's wrong for a woman
to chase after a man.
He won't respect her.

1354
01:39:26,406 --> 01:39:30,497
Forget Mr. Talbot.
Listen to him and
you'll ruin your life.

1355
01:39:30,566 --> 01:39:32,835
But you told me
he was right.

1356
01:39:32,903 --> 01:39:35,969
You said you were
taking his advice.

1357
01:39:36,039 --> 01:39:38,657
Did I?
I don't remember.

1358
01:39:38,726 --> 01:39:40,930
Now, where
were the boys going?

1359
01:39:40,998 --> 01:39:44,740
Paris.
The Deauville Hotel.

1360
01:39:44,806 --> 01:39:48,286
Oh, the Hotel Deauville
in Paris.

1361
01:39:49,990 --> 01:39:51,746
<i>Internazionale prego.</i>

1362
01:39:51,814 --> 01:39:53,919
You're calling Tony.
Lisa--

1363
01:39:53,990 --> 01:39:58,779
I want the Hotel Deauville
in Paris. <i>Si, Parigi.</i>

1364
01:39:58,854 --> 01:40:02,051
When they answer,
ask for him.
You think I should?

1365
01:40:02,118 --> 01:40:03,973
Of course!

1366
01:40:04,038 --> 01:40:08,707
It's like fighting a war.
If you retreat and the enemy
doesn't follow you,

1367
01:40:08,774 --> 01:40:11,425
you've got to turn around
and attack.

1368
01:40:11,494 --> 01:40:14,528
What good is winning the battle
if you lose the war?
<i>Pronto con Parigi.</i>

1369
01:40:14,598 --> 01:40:16,540
<i>Aspetta un momento.</i>

1370
01:40:16,615 --> 01:40:19,876
Why be miserable with someone
you don't love?

1371
01:40:19,942 --> 01:40:24,285
Better to be miserable
with someone you do love!

1372
01:40:26,919 --> 01:40:29,701
Hello? Hello!

1373
01:40:29,766 --> 01:40:31,741
Paris.

1374
01:40:31,814 --> 01:40:35,611
<i>Yes.</i>
<i>Hotel Deauville.</i>

1375
01:40:37,606 --> 01:40:39,810
<i>Yes, I'll hold on.</i>

1376
01:40:53,350 --> 01:40:55,870
Miss Fellini, where--
Apartment 2-A.

1377
01:40:55,942 --> 01:40:59,008
Thank you.
What's she made up for?

1378
01:41:22,534 --> 01:41:24,706
[ Horn Honking ]

1379
01:41:24,838 --> 01:41:28,034
Yes, Operator,
I'm still holding on.

1380
01:41:28,102 --> 01:41:30,077
Hello?

1381
01:41:30,150 --> 01:41:33,052
Hello?
Sandy.

1382
01:41:33,126 --> 01:41:35,395
Hi.

1383
01:41:35,462 --> 01:41:37,502
Oh, it's you.

1384
01:41:37,574 --> 01:41:40,738
Remember I told you
we were going to Paris?

1385
01:41:40,806 --> 01:41:42,748
Did you?

1386
01:41:42,822 --> 01:41:46,302
Well, I couldn't go.
I didn't have your phone number.

1387
01:41:46,374 --> 01:41:48,284
Oh.

1388
01:41:49,798 --> 01:41:52,481
I suddenly realized that
I might never see you again.

1389
01:41:52,550 --> 01:41:56,128
Okay, I know you don't care
if you ever see me again,
but--

1390
01:41:56,198 --> 01:41:59,460
Tony, I don't want
to hurt your feelings--
Don't say another word.

1391
01:41:59,526 --> 01:42:02,755
Just let's have dinner tonight
and the two of us
will sit and talk,

1392
01:42:02,822 --> 01:42:05,156
and maybe get
to know each other.

1393
01:42:05,990 --> 01:42:07,845
Okay?

1394
01:42:07,910 --> 01:42:11,555
<i>[ Phone Ringing ]</i>

1395
01:42:11,622 --> 01:42:14,753
Okay?
What'll I tell Mario?

1396
01:42:16,038 --> 01:42:18,689
Who's Mario?
<i>[ Ringing Continues ]</i>

1397
01:42:18,758 --> 01:42:22,074
My date for tonight.
<i>[ Ringing Continues ]</i>

1398
01:42:22,150 --> 01:42:26,307
Oh. I see.

1399
01:42:26,374 --> 01:42:30,171
But I can cancel it...
if--

1400
01:42:30,246 --> 01:42:31,970
Will ya?

1401
01:42:32,038 --> 01:42:35,835
I won't even answer
the phone.
Good.

1402
01:42:37,190 --> 01:42:40,354
<i>[ Ringing Continues ]</i>

1403
01:42:40,422 --> 01:42:42,909
I promise.
I won't even touch you.

1404
01:43:21,606 --> 01:43:24,475
Which coach do I get on?
What?

1405
01:43:24,550 --> 01:43:26,339
Robert!

1406
01:43:28,646 --> 01:43:32,258
- Robert?
- Look, there she is.
I told you she'd be here.

1407
01:43:32,326 --> 01:43:36,221
- Robert!
- Lisa!

1408
01:43:37,542 --> 01:43:40,641
<i>No, mi lascia passare.</i>
<i>Ma, che diavolo.!</i>

1409
01:43:40,710 --> 01:43:46,045
<i>Senta, biglietto non c'e l'ho.</i>
<i>Ma devo intrare</i>
<i>un momentino solo.</i>

1410
01:43:46,118 --> 01:43:48,125
<i>Ho detto di non.!</i>
<i>Eh, va bene.! Cafone.!</i>

1411
01:43:48,198 --> 01:43:52,671
Darling, I knew
you wouldn't let me down.
My sisters are over there.

1412
01:43:52,742 --> 01:43:56,091
Robert? Robert!

1413
01:43:57,606 --> 01:44:00,640
I'm here!
Robert!

1414
01:44:00,710 --> 01:44:04,190
I'll send you both
a wedding present!

1415
01:44:06,630 --> 01:44:10,907
I must give the fella credit
for one thing.
He's a jolly good loser.

1416
01:44:10,982 --> 01:44:14,528
You stop here
and don't move.
I'll bring my sisters.

1417
01:44:15,686 --> 01:44:17,541
<i>Senta.</i>
<i>A capito.!</i>

1418
01:44:17,606 --> 01:44:20,061
<i>Capito.!</i>

1419
01:44:38,470 --> 01:44:40,641
<i>Ancora lei.</i>
<i>E per il piccino.</i>

1420
01:44:40,710 --> 01:44:44,006
<i>E quando si comincia</i>
<i>a capire ma--</i>
<i>guarda a la mama.</i>

1421
01:44:44,070 --> 01:44:46,688
<i>Ma mi guarda sona abondonata</i>
<i>con questo bambino.</i>

1422
01:44:46,758 --> 01:44:48,645
<i>Giorno della nocce.</i>

1423
01:44:48,710 --> 01:44:51,328
<i>Il padre de questo bambino</i>
<i>sta partendo.</i>

1424
01:44:51,398 --> 01:44:53,983
<i>Malscalzone.! Americano.!</i>
<i>Americano?</i>

1425
01:44:54,054 --> 01:44:57,022
<i>Americano va bene.</i>
<i>Se lei non mi fa passare,</i>
<i>percio lui se ne va.</i>

1426
01:44:57,094 --> 01:44:59,036
<i>Passa, passa, va.!</i>
<i>Grazie, grazie.</i>

1427
01:44:59,109 --> 01:45:00,604
<i>Bravo, guarda.</i>

1428
01:45:00,677 --> 01:45:03,044
I can't let you leave
without talking to her.

1429
01:45:03,110 --> 01:45:05,924
She's just got that
little something extra.

1430
01:45:05,990 --> 01:45:08,291
[ Speaking Italian ]

1431
01:45:08,357 --> 01:45:11,074
That little
something extra!

1432
01:45:11,142 --> 01:45:14,971
This could never happen
in England.
It's this beastly climate!

1433
01:45:15,942 --> 01:45:18,276
<i>Non.</i>

1434
01:45:18,342 --> 01:45:20,709
<i>Eh? Non.</i>

1435
01:45:27,846 --> 01:45:29,275
<i>Ecco lo.!</i>

1436
01:45:29,350 --> 01:45:31,237
<i>Ei lui?</i>
<i>L 'Americano?</i>
<i>Papa.</i>

1437
01:45:31,302 --> 01:45:33,244
<i>L 'Americano.</i>

1438
01:45:36,838 --> 01:45:39,009
<i>Vedi papa.</i>

1439
01:45:59,941 --> 01:46:03,586
No, no.
No, that's not mine.

1440
01:46:03,654 --> 01:46:06,970
Nobody's gonna play
a dirty trick like that on me.

1441
01:46:07,046 --> 01:46:09,250
Nobody's gonna--
That's not mine.

1442
01:46:09,318 --> 01:46:11,390
I'm not gonna leave this train.
I'm gonna go to France.

1443
01:46:11,461 --> 01:46:14,178
I'm gonna go back
to Pittsburgh!

1444
01:46:14,245 --> 01:46:16,417
Lisa, tell him.

1445
01:46:29,990 --> 01:46:32,445
[ Train Whistle Blowing ]

1446
01:46:51,462 --> 01:46:54,048
[ Tires Squealing ]

1447
01:46:57,093 --> 01:46:59,482
He's done it again!

1448
01:47:14,918 --> 01:47:17,602
Sir, I thought you were both
on your way to America.

1449
01:47:17,670 --> 01:47:20,288
You've got two minutes
to get everyone
out of that house.

1450
01:47:20,358 --> 01:47:23,456
I received this letter
from Margaret.
She's forgiven me.

1451
01:47:23,526 --> 01:47:26,395
We might even get married.
I needed the money.

1452
01:47:26,470 --> 01:47:28,444
I said
I want everyone out!

1453
01:47:28,517 --> 01:47:31,485
But they're different.
They're so quiet you
won't notice they're around.

1454
01:47:31,557 --> 01:47:34,591
All right.
If you won't throw them out,
I will.

1455
01:48:06,886 --> 01:48:10,715
Are you sure those
two people are married?

1456
01:48:14,822 --> 01:48:18,684
Sister,
this time I'm sure.